@@eThe Ashborn: Built from What Burned@@N

@@dFrom field interviews conducted along the Cinderteeth lowland@@N
@@dresettlement corridor, compiler unknown, ink smells of sulfur@@N

When the @@rCinderteeth@@N erupted and volcanic fire swept the lowlands,
it did not merely destroy. It @@ychanged@@N. The people caught in the
ashfall who survived — and survival was not common — emerged from
the burning different than they entered it. Their children were
born different. Their children's children more so.

Ashborn skin has the texture of cooled lava — rough, ridged, dark
with veins of dull heat visible beneath the surface in certain
light. Their blood runs hotter than any physician's chart accounts
for. When they are injured, the wound does not bleed openly. It
@@eseals shut with glass-like crust@@N, hardening over the break
the way cooling magma glazes stone. They are not immune to
harm. They are simply accustomed to @@ysurviving it differently@@N.

Near volcanic activity, they feel a directional awareness — a pull,
a warmth in the chest, a knowledge of where the mountain is without
needing to see it. They call it @@ethe mountain's reminder@@N. It is
not worship. It is not fear. It is the body remembering what made it.

Their economy centers on the forge. Not merely metalwork — though
Ashborn metalwork is exceptional — but @@ytransformation@@N itself.
Taking what is raw, broken, or spent and making it into something
that serves. Ore into blade. Rubble into wall. Ash into glass.
The philosophy is indistinguishable from the craft: nothing is
beyond remaking.

@@eMidgaard@@N classified them as "ashfall survivors" in the census
rolls — an administrative category that carries no separate civic
identity and, more importantly, no standing in @@rproperty
disputes@@N. The lowlands they inhabited before the eruption were
reclassified as crown waste. The Ashborn who returned to rebuild
found their claims unrecognized by courts that acknowledged their
existence only as a subcategory of disaster.

They do not organize around this grievance. They do not petition.
They do not protest. They @@econtinue building@@N. The forges are
lit. The roads are repaired. The walls go up. And when Midgaard's
census clerks arrive to count them, they find settlements that
are not supposed to exist, populated by people who are not supposed
to have standing, producing goods that the markets are not
supposed to need.

@@dThe fire took everything. They built it back.@@N
@@dThe records deny them. They are still here.@@N
